defaultData Protection Framework Decision default(DPFDdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe DPFD
default&#xa0;
defaultprovides for the protection of personal data in the area of police and judicial cooperation in criminal matters. It only applies to data which 
defaultis
default shared across borders, not domestically (for example it would apply in an exchange of data between UK and French police forces, but it would not apply to an exchange of data between the Metropolitan and Thames Valley police forces).  It applies to “competent authorities”, which in the 
defaultUK
default includes the police, Courts, the Serious Organised Crime Agency (SOCA) and many government departments. 
defaultA fully-functional law enforcement and criminal justice system within the EU needs to share data in an appropriate manner to protect the public and the rights of individuals. 
defaultThe DPFD achieves this well. It provides a flexible framework which is principles based and places minimum burdens on the criminal justice system. It ensures 
defaultUK
default citizens are protected while simultaneously allowing for the necessary data sharing on criminal matters. By participating in this measure the 
defaultUK
default ensures
default that law enforcement can effectively share data with EU partners without unnecessary red tape or costly burdens
default. 
defaultThe measure is considered “vital” by the Association of Chief Police Officers. In their evidence to the inquiry undertaken by the 
defaultHouse of 
defaultLords E
defaulturopean 
defaultU
defaultnion
default Committee they said “the 
defaultUK
default needs to remain a part of this measure. The reason is that other states may not agree to share such data with any other state under these provisions unless they remain within it”. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe DPFD additionally provides the data protection framework for many other 
defaultpost-Lisbon 
defaultEU JHA measures. These include the Child Sexual Exploitation Directive
default (2012/92/EU)
default, the Victims Directive
default (2012/29/EU) 
defaultand the 
defaultCybercrime Directive
default (2013
default/
default40/EU
default)
default. Participation in the DPFD therefore means that the 
defaultUK
default will be able to fully compliant with these instruments
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultMutual Recognition of Financial Penalties (MRFP)default&#xa0;
defaultThe MRFP ensures that offenders are not able to evade financial penalties
default&#xa0;
defaultsimply because they do not live in the 
defaultMember
default 
defaultState
default where they offend. The measure maintains
default&#xa0;
defaultany deterrent effect of a financial penalty even for people who are resident elsewhere in the 
defaultUnion
default. For example, visitors in the 
defaultUK
default from another 
defaultMember
default 
defaultState
default&#xa0;
defaultmay be less inclined to commit road traffic offences if they know they will likely still have to pay the resulting fine imposed for any offence. 
default&#xa0;defaultThe Framework Decision applies to fines, fines registered as a result of fixed penalty notices, compensation orders, victims surcharge and court costs.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe enforcing 
defaultMember
default 
defaultState
default that collects the financial penalty
default&#xa0;
defaultwill generally
default&#xa0;
defaultkeep it (other than compensation monies that
default&#xa0;
defaultwould generally be
default&#xa0;
defaultremitted back to the victim) as there are often costs associated with enforcement.
default&#xa0;
default The key aim of the measure
default&#xa0;
defaultis to
default&#xa0;
defaultbroaden the effectiveness of financial penalties imposed by Member States
default&#xa0;
defaultOctober 2012
